<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Youth Justice Board</title></head><body><div><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RCH0016</span></h3><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Youth Justice Board for England and Wales (YJB)</span></h3><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Youth Justice Board for England and W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ales (YJB) welcomes this Select Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the opportunity to provide written and oral evidence.   We would be pleased to provide the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Select Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with any further information that may be of assistance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The issue of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disproportionately high numbers of looked after children in the youth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">justice system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is one that the YJB is currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">addressing on a number of levels, which will be detailed below.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role of the YJB is to oversee the youth justice system in England and Wales.  The statutory responsibilities of the YJB incl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ude:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Advising Ministers on the operation of, and standards for, the youth justice system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Monitoring the performance of the youth justice system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Purchasing secure accommodation places for, and placing, children and young people remanded or sentenced by th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e courts to custody</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Identifying and promoting effective practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Commissioning research and publishing information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While the YJB is responsible for overseeing the performance of youth justice services including multi-agency Youth Offending Teams (YOT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s) and secure accommodation providers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">YJB does not directly manage any of the services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee will be aware that Looked After Children (LAC) are disproportionately represented within the youth justice system. Less than 1% of all children i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n England and Wales are looked after at any one time, yet up to one half of all children held in young offenders institutions are, or have previously been, looked after. </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Last year t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he YJB work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with a virtual reference group of YOT practitioners, and have engaged in discussion with the Association of Chief Police Officers and the Magistrates’ Association to draw together evidence of the key issues facing many young people in care, and specifical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly those in residential children’s homes, that unfairly increase the likelihood of them ending up within the youth justice system. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">key issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">anage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ment of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> challenging behaviour in children’s homes and support for young people serving community sentences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Developments are needed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> staff with the skills and support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to:</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">respond to challenging behaviour within children’s homes without relying on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">police</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effectively support a young person through a community sentence, leading to disproportionately high breach rates;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Over-criminalisation of young people in care for minor offences </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Police and courts do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t have flexibility in charging and sen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tencing decisions for minor offences committed by looked-after children and the corporate parent sometimes fails to fulfil their duties towards young people in court;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ut-of-area placement decisions </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ongoing issues with poor care placement decisions that c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an place children at risk of harm to themselves or others, leading to offending</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">nformation sharing between local agencies  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Poor communication and information sharing between placement authorities, YOTs and other children’s services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">upport for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">careleav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ers</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The complex legislative rules concerning which young people hit the criteria as a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">careleaver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’, mean that there are many young people in the youth justice system who do not receive this vital transitional support, and are therefore more likely to conti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nue to offend as adults, leading to the disproportionate representation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the adult prison population (over 25% of the adult population has previously been in care).  Offending rates amongst the general population have significantly reduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> amongst children and young people in the last 5 years, but the gap between looked after children and all children has remained, and they continue to be more than twice as likely to offend. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Developments in the Youth Justice System</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> developments which have within the youth justice system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to begin to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ackle the issues outlined above are summarised below together with the key challenges that remain. These challenges can only be addressed long term through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> partnership working across Gov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ernment, and a commitment from all partners to tackle the issues surrounding looked after children, will we be able to create long term positive change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">anage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ment of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> challenging behaviour in children’s homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, and providing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> support for young people serving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> community sentences</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">YJB continues to work closely with Government Departments and youth justice services to improve the system.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Particular progress has been made regarding behaviour management and the use of restraint across the Secure Estate. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> use of restorative justice is also a key feature of youth justice practice, and is one in which many local youth offending teams have developed an ‘expertise’. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The YJB would therefore recommend that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 13.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all residential care home staff and foster carers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are trained in behaviour management techniques, which include the use of restorative justice where appropriate, and minimal restraint. This would reduce the number of placement breakdowns, and over-reliance on the police, which is a contributory factor to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the higher numbers of convictions for looked after children.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 13.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a Code of Practice for all welfare care placements is adopted to ensure consistency of practice across local authority and private providers (including foster carers). The YJB developed a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Code o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f Practice ‘Managing the Behaviour of Children and Young People in the Secure Estate’ which could be used as a good practice reference.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A working group has recently been established by the Department for Education (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) to review the qualifications fra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mework for residential home staff. Currently, there are significant numbers of staff who have not achieved the basic NVQ Level 3 qualification to work with children and young people. This has led to a workforce who feels unprepared for dealing with the mos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t challenging of behaviours, and young people who are not managed appropriately, leading to high numbers of placement breakdown and higher arrest and conviction rates. The YJB is a member of the working group, and is working with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ensure that the qua</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lifications framework includes a clear and explicit focus on the needs of children and young people in the youth justice system. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">11</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Currently, young people completing a community order while they are in care do not receive the same level of support as yo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ung people living with their parents. This leads to higher than average breach rates</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which then creates further convictions and an increased risk of a custodial sentence. As part of the qualifications framework review, the YJB would recommend that there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is a specific module focusing on the youth justice system, to raise awareness of the implications of failure to provide the appropriate support.  A working protocol between the local youth offending team and residential placement which outlines roles and r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">esponsibilities of respective members of staff would further support improvements in practice.</span></p><p style="line-height:18pt; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Over-criminalisation of young people in care for minor offences </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Key challenges:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The YJB is concerned that p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">olice and courts do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sufficient </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">flexibil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ity in charging and sentencing decisions for minor offences committed by looked-after children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. In addition YOTs and the Magistrates Association report that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the corporate parent sometimes fails to fulfil their duties towards young people in court</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As pre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">viously stated, children and young people in residential homes are very often the most difficult to place, with a number of challenging behaviours and vulnerabilities, as a result of being in the care system for a number of years. Prior to this, many will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have experienced a poor start in life, and some will have been abused or neglected. It is against this backdrop that staff within homes are expected to take on the role of parent/ carer. When a child/ young person displays challenging behaviours, very ofte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n it will escalate, and the police will be called out to diffuse the situation and manage the behaviour. Unfortunately, this has led to many convictions for minor offences, which might otherwise have been addressed within the family unit. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Statutory guidance states that children in care should be accompanied by a social worker (or other local authority representative with who knows the child) in court and should not be sentenced unaccompanied. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Unfortunately, looked after children and young p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eople continue to have inadequate representation from children’s services.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">14</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The YJB would therefore recommend that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> police are given</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> full discretion in prosecuting crimes in residential care-homes and foster care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is currently the case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in schoo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ls. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The YJB would support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> adoption of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Association of Chief Police Officer’s (ACPO) draft guidance ‘Advice for crime reporting by police officers dealing with incidents in children’s homes’, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> piloted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> successfully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by South </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Yorkshire Police. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he production of a working and effective protocol between Children’s Services and the Police would remove many of these issues, and the YJB has played an active role in identifying and disseminating good examples of working protocols a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mongst the youth justice sector. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, 7 local authorities in the South East have recently produced a joint protocol, which is being shared nationally with youth justice partners at the annual national Youth Justice Convention. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should expand their inspection framework to include an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assessment of each</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> care home</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s protocol w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith their local police force,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inappropriate police call-outs and should report on its findings in this area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where a young person is charged with an offence, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulations of the Crown Prosecution Service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(CPS) should be enforced to ensure that they are accountable for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inappropriate referrals to court for minor offences by children in care. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onsideration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is given to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> extending </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CPS guidance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">criminalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of looked-after children in residential care homes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to those in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">foster care.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Corporate Parent prepare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a report summarising the young person’s family and care background, which is submitted alongside the Pre-Sentence Report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in Court</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This would ensure increased court presence of children’s social care at criminal court hearings. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The YJB would welcome the Committee’s support in further exploring this option with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the CPS and the Magistrates Association.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ut-of-area placement d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ecisions </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt 11.25pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">19.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Frequent and inappropriate out of area placements increase a young person’s risk of offending and vulnerability; as highlighted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the high profile reports from the Office of the Children’s Commissioner (OCC) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">child sexual exploitation in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gangs and groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the Joint All Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) Inquiry on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> children who go missing from care. These reports </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">outline</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> particular concerns about the care of children who were placed, often at short notice, in children’s homes a long way fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">om the authorities responsible for their care. Children in such circumstances were vulnerable to going missing from their placements and could be targeted for exploitation. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt 11.25pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">20.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has been proactive in tackling this issue, and recently two key consul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tations were launched </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which consider proposals to amend the Care Planning, Placement and Case Review (England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) Regulations 2010. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> propos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> amendments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are designed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to ensure that where looked after children are placed out of authority in distant placemen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ts they are effectively safeguarded and their welfare is promoted. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The YJB has completed a response to the consultation, and welcomes the proposals. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The second consultation proposes to amend the Children’s Homes Regulations 2001 (as amended) (“the Children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s Homes Regulations”), with a related amendment to the Care Standards Act 2000 (Registration) (England) Regulations 2010 (“the Registration Regulations”), and a minor amendment to the Fostering Services (England) Regulations 2011 (covered at paragraph 12)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (“the Fostering Services Regulations”). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The amendments are necessary to improve collaboration and partnership between children’s homes and services in their local communities so that there are effective safeguards in place for the vulnerable group of chi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ldren relying on residential care.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The YJB welcomes the proposed changes.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt 11.25pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">21.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Specific consideration needs to be given to the issues faced when a young person is placed ‘over the border’ in Wales or vice versa. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As the Welsh Government and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are increasin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gly working to different sets of regulations, it is important that they work together to ensure consistency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actice for this group of young people, who otherwise run the risk of ‘falling through the net’. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt 11.25pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">22.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The YJB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has identified and disseminated pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">otocols </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around out of area placements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> through regional effective practice forums, our online</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Effective Practice Library, and will be running a workshop on this at the Youth Justice Convention in November 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nformation sharing between local agencies  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">23</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Poor communication and information sharing between placement authorities, YOTs and other children’s services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has been an unfortunate feature of care for looked after children for many years. There are a number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tiatives underway to improve practic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e, and the YJB have been involved in developing each of these. Firstly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e Care Planning, Placement and Case Review (England) Regulations 2010 proposes to amend current arrangements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for out of borough placements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ich can result a host authority receiving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">notification </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">after a child </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">placed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">24</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is proposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">placing authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will be required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to consult with the authority where the child will be placed, prior to placement. The consultation document also proposes to ensure effective notification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> arrangements are in place, and that all relevant services are consulted as part of the assessment of the potential move. The YJB has strongly recommended that where a young person is open to youth justice supervision, consultation with the home and host Y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">OT should take place, and there should be effective protocols in place to back this up.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">25</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In DFE’s amendments to the Children’s Homes Regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2001,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there are two specific provisions which will impact on information sharing. The first is the proposal that children’s homes should be required to notify the authority where they are located, whenever a child is admitted or leaves the home. The YJB has req</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uested that the YOT should also be notified, to ensure joined up working, and so that unnecessary enforcement action is not taken on an Order, which could lead to further criminalisation of a young person. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">26</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The second proposal is for an annual “risk a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssessment” of the area where a home is located. This work would require liaison with the local police and with local authority children’s services responsible for safeguarding. Again, the YJB has suggested that liaison takes place with the YOT, who will ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve information about a young person’s associates, and whether the placement would place them at further risks such as gang involvement or child sexual exploitation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">27</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The proposals contained within the two consultations are very positive, and the YJB wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uld encourage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to require areas to consult with youth offending teams as a routine matter. The provision of effective and active information sharing and joint working protocols is crucial in dealing with this issue. The YJB has contacted all 158 YOTs to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> identify good practice in this area. Where protocols are in place to oversee information sharing, staff report that this has improved joint working between professionals to manage a young person. As such, the YJB has highlighted two particular areas of go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">od practice, and invited them to attend the Youth Justice Annual Convention in November 2013. Following the workshop the YJB will produce a model protocol to be shared with all youth offending teams and partners. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">upport for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">careleavers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">28</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The complex l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">egislative rules concerning which young people hit the criteria as a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">careleaver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’ in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Care Leavers (England) Regulations 2010, mean that many professionals do not understand which young people are entitled to support. It is therefore no surprise tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t many young people do not understand their own entitlements. The current rules result in a large group of young people who have previously been ‘looked after’, but are not entitled to support as a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">careleaver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’. This is concerning, and the YJB would recomm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">end an urgent review into the current legislative framework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">29</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> also proposes to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">amend Part 7 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the Care Planning, Placement and Case Review (England) Regulations 2010, in regard to 16 and 17 year old looked after children, so that a decision to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cease looking after this group of children is not put into effect until it has been approved and signed off by the Director of Children’s Services. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This will ensure that there is an appropriate pathway plan in place before a young person ceases to be looke</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d after. This is an encouraging step in the right direction, but we would recommend wholesale changes to the current legislative framework are required if the state is exercise its duty as a corporate parent and ensure that this vulnerable group of young p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eople make a successful transition to adulthood.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">30</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Association have completed some work to address the disproportionate numbers of care leavers in the criminal justice system. They have established a peer mentoring scheme at a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">adult prisons, which is showing early signs of success. Former </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work with their peers in custody, and help them resettle and seek the appropriate support upon release. The YJB are currently in discussions with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Association about t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he potential to adapt the scheme for the under 18 Secure Estate.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">31</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Foundation recently received funding from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to provide support to 9 local authorities to better address the needs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over the coming 12 months. The YJB are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in close contact with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Foundation to ensure that the local youth offending teams are involved in this project, and also to identify any lessons learnt and good practice which could then be disseminated amongst all other YOTs. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Foundation have created a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Charter, which they would like all local authorities to sign up to. The YJB will promote the charter amongst YOTs so that they can discuss signing up to it at a local level.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">32</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">      </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A key concern highlighted by part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ners is that when a young person moves from YOT Supervision to Probation Supervision upon turning 18, much of the key information surrounding their care status, and support is lost. This leaves </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> particularly vulnerable. The YJB have undertaken s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ignificant work in this area, and in partnership with NOMS, recently announced a number of measures and resources to tackle this issue. Guidance for young people on community orders who move to probation has been developed. A similar set of guidance has al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">so been developed for when young people move from the under 18 estate to the adult YOI estate. In addition a secure web-based portal, ‘Y2A’, has been created to allow for the safe transfer of all information on a young person to the adult estate. These are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> important and significant steps forward in ensuring that the transition from child to adult support for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is more effective.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Impact of LASPOA</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">33</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Committee will be aware that following the implementation of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Pu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nishment of Offenders Act 2012 LASPOA, from April 2013, all remanded young people receive LAC status. Early indications from the Secure Estate are that this has led to increases in the proportion of LAC young people within custody, and then attracting leav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing care support upon release. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is therefore important that any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Government response considers the impact that LASPOA is having on an already stretched youth justice system.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">s and Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">34</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">There is some encouraging work taking plac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e to reduce the disproportionate numbers of looked after children in the youth justice system. The YJB are involved in many key pieces of work and have developed some good practice examples to meet the needs of looked after children and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">careleavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">youth justice system. However, there continues to be a need to work with local partners and government departments to highlight the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">overcriminalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> of looked after children in the youth justice system to ensure that this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> issue is adequately addressed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All residential care home staff and foster carers are trained in behaviour management techniques and restorative justice;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Development of a Code of Practice for all welfare care placements, including foster carers to oversee the appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> management of behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and effective use of restorative justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The police are given full discretion in prosecuting crimes in residential care-homes and foster care, in line with the Association of Chief Police Officer’s (ACPO) draft guidance ‘Advice fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r crime reporting by police officers dealing with incidents in children’s homes’,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A specific module on the youth justice system to be included in the qualifications framework for residential staff;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Up to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> date, working protocols are established between yout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h offending teams and their local residential placements which outlines roles and responsibilities of respective members of staff;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Extend CPS guidance on the criminalisation of looked-after children in residential care homes to those in foster care;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Explor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e possibility of Corporate Parent preparing a report summarising the young person’s family and care background, which is submitted alongside the Pre-Sentence Report;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When an out of area placement is being considered and the young person is open to youth ju</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stice supervision, consultation with the home and host YOT should take place, and there should be effective protocols in place to back this up; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.37pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An urgent review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to take place</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> into the current legislative framework surrounding care leavers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:105%; margin:0pt 0pt 7pt; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">9</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Department for Education (2011) Children looked after by local authorities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> year ending 31 March 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Hart, D (2011) ‘Into the Breach: the enforcement of statutory orders in the youth justice system’, p58, The Prison Reform Trust.</span></p></body></html>